The decision to graduate in two years was practical: my sister began college immediately after I finished my undergraduate degree, and completing my degree earlier eased my family's financial burden. The pressure to graduate early pushed me to take a large course load in my undergraduate studies. This timeline taught me to be resourceful. It forced me to identify research opportunities quickly, build relationships with mentors, and seek out communities where I could learn from others. Looking back, graduating early while maintaining my research and community commitments shaped my approach to navigating challenges, and I believe these same qualities will aid me as a graduate student.

Managing coursework while pursuing research, founding the Algorithms Club, and participating in competitive programming often required persistence. Although it sometimes spread me thin, working on various projects helped me gain perspective on each one in my life and to grow in each very quickly. One of the most valuable takeaways from my undergraduate years was meeting people with different academic backgrounds in research and through running the club, and seeing how different collaborators offered unique perspectives. In both my research and the Algorithms Club, I saw how different approaches to problems and reading papers led to better discussions and insights. In each club meeting, we read papers in both new and familiar areas of theoretical computer science, forcing us to engage with new content. These discussions exposed us all to new ideas and influenced my approach to research. In the Multimodal Interactions Lab, I also introduced new students to HCI literature and research tools, helping them explore the field. 

In the Algorithms Club, I worked to make theoretical computer science accessible to students from computer science, mathematics, and other engineering disciplines. Working with people who from different academic backgrounds and with a variety of research interests often led to productive research discussions by viewing questions through different lenses. As a graduate student, I'm eager to continue working with people across subdisciplines within theoretical computer science, to mentor students encountering new research areas, and to foster inclusive problem-solving communities. The persistence and resourcefulness I developed through my accelerated timeline will serve me well, but what I value most is learning to approach research alongside others who challenge my thinking and broaden my perspective.
